Anonymous Fri 28 Apr 2023 01:46:32 No.56087320 Report
Quoted By:
>>56086727
Bad grammar. Bad spelling. Verb tenses getting mixed up from one sentence to the next. Also authors who tell instead of show. Exposition is commonly needed when we get into a story that isn't set in the present day of where the reader happens to live. But there's a right way to do exposition and a wrong way. Grabbing the microphone out of the viewpoint characters' hands to go on for six paragraphs about how this world is kind of like ours, but magic is real, and creatures of legend and myth sometimes come into the world normal people know, that shit drives me crazy. Don't speak to us as an omniscient author about how there's magic and it's real. Have a character see real magic. Don't lecture us about the seven kinds of dragons. Have a character meet a dragon.

Anonymous Fri 28 Apr 2023 03:31:01 No.56089615 Report
Quoted By: >>56089710 >>56089937 >>56090766
>>56088704
So, based on my experiences when I first started out, the issue with getting criticism as a beginner is that there can be an overwhelming amount of information and corrections to bear. That’s not good for improvements at all; it’s really better to just focus on something one at a time and get that nailed down before fixing the next bad thing.

I’ll leave it at 2 things for now: 3Difying the head, and proportions.

I know you said you haven’t moved onto 3D shapes yet, so it makes sense that currently your faces are lacking form. Grind out some spheres, cylinders, and cubes first. Remember for cubes you have to get the lines to converge at a certain point in the horizon; Draw-a-box exercises are fantastic for this. Spheres can be 3D-ified by having that plus-shaped mask you see when people construct faces, but also remember to loop that + shape to the rear side of the sphere (as though it’s made of glass and you used a marker to draw a two perpendicular lines along its entire circumference).

After warming up with 3D shapes you can apply them to faces. Get reference images of animals you like, the less fur the better (fur gets in the way; Mexican hairless dogs are god tier for seeing how a dogs). What I’m about to say is easier digitally but it’s still possible traditionally by printing out the references, and then using tracing paper over them (get em from your local art shop). You can also do this for (I stress) GOOD ARTISTS WHO KNOW WHAT THEY’RE DOING, but if you’re printing from a public place you better make sure it’s sfw (or no one’s around).

See what I did in the attached image? You draw over the reference but break it down into the 3D shapes you see. For me it’s a sphere for the head, a trapezoidal box for the muzzle, and a triangular ramp for the lower jaw. Find what shapes work for you; I’d recommend just spheres, cylinders, and boxes for now, you can advance your shapes further as you up your command of 3D.

Anonymous Fri 28 Apr 2023 03:31:55 No.56089634 Report
Quoted By: >>56089710 >>56089937 >>56090766 >>56096461
>>56088704
Remember that you’re not tracing. You’re analyzing how an image is constructed in the 3D space. If you’re not tired from your deconstruction exercises you can then try to draw the shapes freehand (instead of over the reference; but you can still use the reference as… Reference) to see if you can recreate the shapes.

The reason why I recommend combining this exercise with faces is because 1. It’ll be less boring, 2. It’ll get you better at faces faster, and 3. Getting good at drawing 3D shapes is one thing, but you need to learn how to apply them too.

Proportionally, your torso length and the head-to-torso ratio is great; but the upper leg seems way too long, both arms are too thin, and the screen-left arm is a little too long (if it was straightened it’d appear a little too long for her body). Proportions is something you sort naturally of get good at the longer you draw, but you can still employ a couple of pointers. Like GENERALLY the upper body is 3.5~4 heads long, and the legs are 4~5 heads long (depending on how tall you want to make the character). Place little lines at the top and bottom and box your character from head to foot within those lines. Arms when straightened should have hands reaching the groin. And if you use references, always pay attention to the negative space. Sometimes they reveal a lot more about the figure than what’s actually there.
